Find sources: &#160;"Coachella, California"&#160;–&#160;news&#160;· newspapers&#160;· books&#160;· scholar&#160;· JSTOR (April 2019) ( [Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal) )

The city was founded as Woodspur in 1876, when the [Southern Pacific Railroad](/Southern_Pacific_Railroad) built a [rail siding](/Rail_siding) on the site. In the 1880s the indigenous [Cahuilla](/Cahuilla) tribe sold their land plots to the railroads for new lands east of the current town site, and in the 1890s, a few hundred [traqueros](/Traquero) settled along the tracks. In 1901, the citizens of Woodspur voted on a new name for their community and at a town hall meeting settled on "Coachella". &#91;9&#93;

The origin of the name Coachella is unclear. Some locals believe it was a misspelling of conchilla , a Spanish word for the small white snail shells found in the valley's sandy soil, vestiges of a lake that dried up over 3,000 years ago.

Coachella began as a 2.5-square-mile (6.5&#160;km 2 ) territory gridded out on the mesquite-covered desert floor. Coachella became a city in 1946. During the incorporation voting process, the first city council was tentatively elected.

In the 1950s Coachella begin to expand into its range, about 32 square miles (83&#160;km 2 ), an area which contained large year-round agricultural corporate farms and fruit groves, particularly of [citrus](/Citrus) (lemons, oranges, grapefruit) and [date palms](/Date_palm).

By the 1980 census, Coachella's population had reached at least 10,000 due to relatively slow population growth. Due to a high percentage of Hispanics in the city, Coachella was a scene of [Chicano](/Chicano) political activism. The agricultural area surrounding Coachella was where the [United Farm Workers](/United_Farm_Workers) union staged strikes and protests, including visits by UFW leader [César Chávez](/C%C3%A9sar_Ch%C3%A1vez) in the 1960s and 1970s. In 2018, Harrison Street (the main street in town) was renamed for him. &#91;10&#93;

In 1995, state and federal officials designated Coachella as part of the [Coachella Valley Enterprise Zone](/Coachella_Valley_Enterprise_Zone) to boost economic activity and entice businesses to relocate to this rural city which was once home to several fruit shipping plants.

In 2010, a Coca-Cola bottling facility (a [LEED](/Leadership_in_Energy_and_Environmental_Design) certified building) was added to the city's new light industry facilities, a boon in the rapid-growth community which has a currently troubled economy. &#91;11&#93;

## Geography

According to the [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), the city has a total area of 30.08 square miles (77.9&#160;km 2 ), all of it land. &#91;3&#93;

The elevation is 68 feet (21&#160;m) below sea level, as the eastern half of the Coachella Valley is below sea level. The saltwater lake, [Salton Sea](/Salton_Sea), 10 miles (16&#160;km) south of Coachella, is 228 feet (69&#160;m) below sea level.

## Climate

This climate is dominated in all months by the subtropical [anticyclone](/Anticyclone), or subtropical high, with its descending air, elevated inversions, and clear skies. Although only a short distance from [Banning, California](/Banning,_California) which has a warm-summer Mediterranean climate, it also lies in a [rainshadow](/Rainshadow) that allows Coachella only about one-fourth the precipitation of Banning. The [Köppen Climate Classification](/K%C3%B6ppen_Climate_Classification) subtype for this climate is ["Bwh"](/Desert_climate). (Tropical and Subtropical Desert Climate). &#91;12&#93;

