## Demographics

• This section needs additional citations for [verification](/Wikipedia:Verifiability) . Please help [improve this article](/Special:EditPage/Coachella,_California) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners) in this section. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed. (September 2009) ( [Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal) )

Despite its image for Mexican immigration, a large percentage are US citizens, born and raised in Coachella. A multi-generational [Mexican American](/Mexican_American) culture has taken root in the town, including a significant portion particularly from the Mexican state of [Sinaloa](/Sinaloa). &#91;14&#93;

Much of the population consists of younger Latino families (an estimated 90 percent of [Hispanic](/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans) origin) and, in the outlying areas, migrant farm workers. The city is officially bilingual in the English and Spanish languages, though city council meetings are held in English. Historically, apart from the Hispanic/Latino and/or [Native Americans](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States), other ethnic groups in Coachella included [Arabs](/Arab-American), [Armenians](/Armenian_American), [Filipinos](/Filipino_American), [Italians](/Italian-American), [Japanese](/Japanese_American), and recent immigrants from Southeast Asia and the former [Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia](/Socialist_Federal_Republic_of_Yugoslavia).

