## Sports

The [Coachella Football Club](/Coachella_FC) is a semi-professional [American soccer](/American_soccer) team based in Coachella. Founded in January 2024, the team plays in [USL League Two](/USL_League_Two), the fourth tier of the [American Soccer Pyramid](/American_Soccer_Pyramid). &#91;34&#93;

## Government and politics

In the [California State Legislature](/California_State_Legislature), Coachella is in [the 18th senatorial district](/California%27s_18th_senatorial_district), represented by [Democrat](/California_Democratic_Party)&#32;[Steve Padilla](/Steve_Padilla), and in [the 36th Assembly district](/California%27s_36th_State_Assembly_district), represented by [Republican](/California_Republican_Party)&#32;[Jeff Gonzalez](/Jeff_Gonzalez). &#91;35&#93;

In the [United States House of Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives), Coachella is in [California's 25th congressional district](/California%27s_25th_congressional_district), represented by [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States))&#32;[Raul Ruiz](/Raul_Ruiz_(politician)). &#91;36&#93;

## Education

Coachella is served by the [Coachella Valley Unified School District](/Coachella_Valley_Unified_School_District), &#91;37&#93; based in [Thermal, California](/Thermal,_California). Its main high school is [Coachella Valley High School](/Coachella_Valley_High_School) (with 2900 students) followed by a new high school, [Desert Mirage High School](/Desert_Mirage_High_School), about 5 miles to the south; its three middle schools are Cahuilla Desert Academy, Toro Canyon, and Bobby Duke. Elementary schools include Cesar Chavez, Coral Mountain Academy, Palm View, Peter Pendleton, Valle Del Sol, Valley View, Westside and in nearby Thermal, John Kelley.

The Coachella Valley Adult School, in operation since 1952, is the third-largest adult school in Riverside County. It offers seven levels of [English as a Second Language](/English_language_learning_and_teaching) (ESL), and has offered citizenship classes for over 20 years. In the last ten years, over 1,500 people completed citizenship classes at the school and submitted [N-400](/Form_N-400) forms.

## Public safety

The [Riverside County Sheriff's Department](/Riverside_County_Sheriff%27s_Department) provides law enforcement for the city from the nearby Thermal Regional Station. The original Coachella Police Department was absorbed by the Sheriff's Department in 1998.

The city of Coachella contracts for fire and paramedic services with the Riverside County Fire Department through a cooperative agreement with [CAL FIRE](/California_Department_of_Forestry_and_Fire_Protection). &#91;38&#93;

## Transportation

Near Coachella, a new four-lane expressway, [State Route 86](/California_State_Route_86), was built for international trucking from [Mexicali, Mexico](/Mexicali,_Mexico) to Los Angeles or Arizona. Referred to as the "NAFTA highway" (in reference to the [North American Free Trade Agreement](/North_American_Free_Trade_Agreement) took effect in 1994), it replaces an older and less safe two-lane road known as the "killer highway, deadly highway, and death highway" where over 400 auto accident fatalities took place since 1980.

A plan is being developed for new passenger rail service that would span approximately 144 miles from Los Angeles Union Station (LAUS) to Coachella. Construction would take an estimated ten years following completion of an [Environmental Impact Statement](/Environmental_Impact_Statement)/[Environmental Impact Report](/Environmental_Impact_Report) (EIS/EIR). &#91;39&#93;

## In popular culture

In 2001 [Huell Howser](/Huell_Howser) Productions, in association with [KCET](/KCET)/Los Angeles, featured Coachella in [California's Gold](/California%27s_Gold) ; the program is available as a VHS videorecording. &#91;40&#93;

